         <abstract>
            <p>Municipal bond rating agencies are under attack along with the doctrine of tax immunity for interest on local government debt. By enhancing the advantage of tax immunity, federal policy is the underlying reason for such so-called "abuses of the tax-exempt privilege" as arbitrage and advance refunding. Local finance is being demoralized by the substitution of "corporate authority" for collective responsibility. Criteria of municipal general obligation credit analysis are not adaptable to the evaluation of "corporate authority" debt, which could bring local control of public finance to an end.</p>
          </abstract>
